        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"total_weeks\":9,\"goal_description\":\"Late Summer Half Marathon (1:45:00 goal)\",\"phases\":[{\"phase_type\":\"Build\",\"weeks\":4,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":35,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":48,\"intensity_distribution\":\"80% easy / 20% hard\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"LongRun\",\"Tempo\",\"Interval\",\"Recovery\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":360,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":295,\"notes\":\"With 9 weeks to race day and a solid 35 km base, we go straight into a build phase — no need to spend time re-establishing aerobic foundation. The focus here is progressive overload: long runs extending toward 18–19 km, one structured quality session per week (Tempo on Saturdays or Intervals on Tuesdays), and three easy/recovery runs filling the remaining days. Volume rises by roughly 8–10% per week, with a deload in week 4. Easy runs are paced using Daniels-Gilbert zones at approximately 6:00/km to protect aerobic adaptation and honor your IT-band history. The long run is your most important session each week — treat it as the anchor. Quality sessions target half-marathon specific adaptations: lactate threshold work and aerobic capacity. Monday and Thursday serve as easy bookends around Tuesday quality. Saturday carries the second quality session or long run depending on the week.\",\"includes_deload\":true},{\"phase_type\":\"Peak\",\"weeks\":3,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":48,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":52,\"intensity_distribution\":\"75% easy / 25% hard\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"LongRun\",\"Tempo\",\"Interval\",\"Recovery\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":355,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":290,\"notes\":\"The peak phase is where race-specific fitness consolidates. Weekly volume reaches its ceiling around 50–52 km — high enough to stress the half-marathon energy systems without accumulating fatigue you can't shed before race day. The long run peaks at 19–20 km in week 6, which is the physiological sweet spot for a 1:45 half marathon goal. Tuesday Intervals shift toward longer cruise intervals (1200m–2000m) at Daniels-Gilbert threshold pace (~4:50–4:55/km), reinforcing your ability to sustain goal race effort. Saturday Tempo runs of 6–8 km at approximately 4:58–5:02/km build lactate clearance capacity. Easy days remain genuinely easy — the Daniels-Gilbert zone pace-zone index puts your easy ceiling at 5:55–6:00/km, and drifting faster on these days is the most common mistake at this stage. No deload mid-phase given the short overall window, but effort perception guides daily decisions.\",\"includes_deload\":false},{\"phase_type\":\"Taper\",\"weeks\":2,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":38,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":22,\"intensity_distribution\":\"85% easy / 15% hard\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"LongRun\",\"Tempo\",\"Recovery\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":355,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":295,\"notes\":\"The taper is an active investment in race-day performance, not a rest period. Volume drops sharply — about 25% in week 8, then another 40% in race week — while intensity is preserved in shorter doses. This allows glycogen stores to top off, micro-damage to repair, and neuromuscular freshness to return. Week 8 includes one short Tempo run (4 km at goal half-marathon pace) and a final long run of 14 km at easy Daniels-Gilbert zone effort. Race week (week 9) features only easy runs of 5–6 km on Monday and Thursday, a short 3 km shake-out with 4×100m strides on Saturday, and rest on Sunday before the Saturday August 8th race. The taper blues are real — legs may feel flat or heavy mid-taper. That is a sign the process is working, not a sign of detraining. Trust the accumulated fitness from the previous 7 weeks.\",\"includes_deload\":false}],\"rationale\":\"This 9-week plan is built around your three strongest assets: a consistent 35 km weekly base, a demonstrated ability to handle structured intensity, and a recent 10K time of 47:30. Using the Daniels-Gilbert pace-zone index, your 47:30 10K projects to a half-marathon finish of approximately 1:44–1:46 at current fitness — meaning a 1:45:00 goal is realistic and well-calibrated, not a stretch. The plan uses a Build → Peak → Taper structure compressed into 9 weeks. We skip a dedicated Base phase because your existing aerobic foundation is sufficient; spending weeks re-establishing base fitness you already have would be a missed opportunity given the short runway. Volume progression is capped at 10% per week to protect against IT-band flare-ups, which your history flags as a risk when load ramps too quickly. Every third or fourth week includes a volume reduction of roughly 20% to allow connective tissue and neuromuscular systems to absorb the preceding load. The 80/20 intensity split (easy to hard) is the evidence-based backbone of the plan. Two quality sessions per week — one on Tuesday (your preferred structured day) and one on Saturday (your second preferred day) — provide sufficient stimulus without overcrowding your schedule. Wednesday and Friday rest days create built-in recovery buffers. The long run on Sundays is your aerobic cornerstone, extending progressively to 19–20 km before the taper. Paces are derived directly from your Daniels-Gilbert pace-zone index and are non-negotiable in both directions: easy runs must stay easy, and quality sessions must hit their target windows to generate the intended physiological stimulus.\",\"warnings\":\"IT-band watch: Your history of IT-band tightness during volume ramps means the 10% weekly increase cap is especially important for you — not just a guideline. If you notice any lateral knee tightness, flag it immediately rather than running through it. Reducing a single week's volume by 15–20% is far less costly than losing 2–3 weeks to a flare-up. Heat and humidity: A late-summer race in August means training through July and early August heat. Easy pace targets from the Daniels-Gilbert zones may need to be adjusted by 15–30 seconds per km on high heat-humidity days — run by effort (conversational breathing) rather than pace on those days, and count the session as a full quality effort regardless of splits. This is not optional; heat adaptation and injury prevention outweigh hitting a pace number on a Tuesday in July. Race-week travel or logistics: If August 8th involves travel, build that into your recovery planning for race week. Sleep, hydration, and time-zone adjustments matter more in the final 72 hours than any additional training. Medical: If any pain (not general fatigue or muscle soreness) persists beyond 2–3 days, consult a physiotherapist or sports medicine physician before continuing. This plan is not a substitute for professional medical evaluation.\"}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
